Exercise 1: Primate milk quality

A. Specify the models

setwd("/Users/mini/Desktop/PSYCH 463/Problem set/13")
d <- read.csv("PS_13_galapagos.csv", header = TRUE)

logit <- function(x) 1/(1+exp(-(x)))
log.area <- log(d$AREA)
log.elev <- log(d$ELEV)
log.distnear <- log(d$DISTNEAR)
log.areanear <- log(d$AREANEAR)

area <- (log.area - mean(log.area)) / (2 * sd(log.area))
elev <- (log.elev - mean(log.elev)) / (2 * sd(log.elev))
distnear <- (log.distnear - mean(log.distnear)) / (2 * sd(log.distnear))
areanear <- (log.areanear - mean(log.areanear)) / (2 * sd(log.areanear))

y_i ~ binom(a, N)
## y_i ~ binom(a, N)
y_i ~ binom(a + ba * area_i, N)
## y_i ~ binom(a + ba * area_i, N)
y_i ~ binom(a + be * elev_i, N)
## y_i ~ binom(a + be * elev_i, N)
y_i ~ binom(a + bdistnear * distnear_i, N)
## y_i ~ binom(a + bdistnear * distnear_i, N)
y_i ~ binom(a + bareanear * areanear_i, N)
## y_i ~ binom(a + bareanear * areanear_i, N)
y_i ~ binom(a + bnear * areanear_i * distnear_i, N)
## y_i ~ binom(a + bnear * areanear_i * distnear_i, N)

B. Simulate data from the models

a <- 0.5
ba <- 2
be <- 6
bdistnear <- 4
barearnear <- 3.5
bnear <- 9

sim.intercept <- rbinom(length(d$TOTAL),
                      prob = 0.5,
                      size = d$TOTAL)

sim.area <- rbinom(30,
                      prob = logit(a + ba * area),
                      size = d$TOTAL)

sim.elev <- rbinom(30, 
                    prob = logit(a + be * elev),
                    size = d$TOTAL)

sim.dis <- rbinom(30, 
                    prob = logit(a + bdistnear * distnear),
                    size = d$TOTAL)

sim.areanear <- rbinom(30, 
                    prob = logit(a + barearnear * areanear),
                    size = d$TOTAL)

sim.disareanear <- rbinom(30, 
                    prob = logit(a + bnear * distnear * areanear),
                    size = d$TOTAL)

par(mfrow = c(1, 5))
plot(sim.area / d$TOTAL ~ log(d$AREA))
plot(sim.elev / d$TOTAL ~ log(d$ELEV))
plot(sim.dis / d$TOTAL ~ log(d$DISTNEAR))
plot(sim.areanear / d$TOTAL ~ log(d$AREANEAR))
plot(sim.disareanear / d$TOTAL ~ I(log(d$DISTNEAR) * log(d$AREANEAR)))

D. Validate code

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

#a
rep.m <- function(a) {
y1 <- rbinom(length(d$TOTAL),
              prob = logit(a),
              size = d$TOTAL)
m1 <- mle2(y1 ~ dbinom(size = d$TOTAL,
                       prob = logit(a)),
           start = list(a = 0.5),
           data = list(y1 = y1))
coef(m1)
}

a.p <- 0.5
a.reps <- replicate(99, rep.m(a.p))
hist(a.reps, breaks = 50)
lines(c(a.p, a.p), c(0, 10000), lwd = 3, col = "orange")

#ba
rep.m <- function(ba) {
y2 <- rbinom(length(d$TOTAL),
              prob = logit(a + ba * area),
              size = d$TOTAL)
m2 <- mle2(y2 ~ dbinom(size = d$TOTAL,
                       prob = logit(a + ba * area)),
           start = list(a = 0, ba = 0),
           data = list(y2 = y2))
coef(m2)["ba"]
}

ba.p <- 0.6
ba.reps <- replicate(99, rep.m(ba.p))
hist(ba.reps, breaks = 50)
lines(c(ba.p, ba.p), c(0, 10000), lwd = 3, col = "orange")

E. Fit models to the actual data

mintercept <- mle2(NATIVE ~ dbinom(prob = logit(a),
                                     size = TOTAL),
                   start = list(a = 0), 
                   data = d)

marea <- mle2(NATIVE ~ dbinom(size = TOTAL,
                        prob = logit(a + ba * area)), 
                        start = list(a = 0, ba = 0),             
                        data = d)

melev <- mle2(NATIVE ~ dbinom(size = TOTAL,
                        prob = logit(a + be * elev)), 
                        start = list(a = 0, be = 0),             
                        data = d)

mdis <- mle2(NATIVE ~ dbinom(size = TOTAL,
                        prob = logit(a + bdistnear * distnear)), 
                        start = list(a = 0, bdistnear = 0),             
                        data = d)

mareanear <- mle2(NATIVE ~ dbinom(size = TOTAL,
                        prob = logit(a + barearnear * areanear)), 
                        start = list(a = 0, barearnear = 0),            
                        data = d)

mdisareanear <- mle2(NATIVE ~ dbinom(size = TOTAL,
                     prob = logit(a + bnear * distnear *
                                    areanear)), 
                     start = list(a = 0, bnear = 0),
                     data = d)

F. Compare the models and interpret their estimates

AICtab(mintercept, marea, melev, mdis, mareanear, mdisareanear, weights = TRUE, nobs = sum(d$TOTAL))
##              dAIC df weight
## marea         0.0 2  1     
## melev        21.3 2  <0.001
## mareanear    54.5 2  <0.001
## mdis         61.1 2  <0.001
## mintercept   63.0 1  <0.001
## mdisareanear 64.8 2  <0.001
exp(coef(marea))
##         a        ba 
## 0.6890061 0.4198628

Answer: Based on the AIC model comparison, the marea model is the best. It has the lower AIC value and dominates the Akaike weight (100%). The second and third hypothesis have weak support because the weights are all under 0.1%. Back transforming the intercept value gives us the baseline odds of surviving. The endemic species begins with a baseline odds of 0.689 of successfully surviving on island. As the area increase, then odds decrease by 0.42 times. It support the first hypothesis: larger islands have proportionately fewer endemic species.

Exercise 2. East African livestock

A.

data <- read.csv("PS_13_rinder.csv", header = TRUE)
data$s <- ifelse(data$stock == "large", 1, 0)

m1 <- mle2(data$mortality ~ dbinom(prob = logit(a + b * data$s),
                                 size = data$n),
           start = list(a = 0, b = 0), data = data)

exp(coef(m1))
##         a         b 
## 1.0313862 0.8825115
logit(0.031+(-0.125))
## [1] 0.4765173
0.5077253-0.4765173
## [1] 0.031208

Answer: The stocks have a baseline of 1.03 odds of surviving. If the stock is large, the odds of surviving decrease by 0.88 times. On average, the probability of death of small stocks is 0.5077, and 0.476 for large stocks. The expected difference in probability of death between small stock and large stock is 0.0312. Therefore, The hypothesis that small stock survive better is proved to be false using the data set.

B.

m2 <- mle2(data$mortality ~ dbinom(size = n,
                                 prob = logit(a)),
                                 start = list(a = 0), data = data)

C.

AICtab(m1, m2, base = TRUE, weights = TRUE)
##    AIC   dAIC  df weight

## m2 876.1   4.7 1  0.089

Answer: The m1 model is better than m2, and it has 91.1% weight. It means that stock size is a good predictor to explain the data set, but still there are other factors not including in the model (weight is not 1).

#m1 <- lmer(mortality ~ stock + ( 1 | herd), data = data)

m.glmm <- glmer(cbind(mortality, n - mortality) ~ (1|herd) + 
                  s + (0 + s|herd),
              data = data, family = binomial)

E. (ii)

Answer: The mean is -0.6571, which is the overall intercept, standard deviation is 0.3136 as the residual variation among herds. By using this two data, a normal distribution (GLMM makes assumption of normal distribution) from which the random intercepts for each herd can be drawn.

E. (iii)

Answer: One unit of increase in large stock would increase the mortality rate by 15%, compared to small stock with a standard deviation of 0.05 when controlling the effect among herds. It is not the same. The direction of the effect of being large stock or small stock (stock size) is even opposite.
